### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

common

### Description

Description
Ability to format a date to a specific time zone without knowing the time zone offset of that specific date.

Describe the solution you'd like
before:

const date1 = new Date('2022-08-28T15:00:00');
const date2 = new Date('2022-12-28T15:00:00');
const format = 'short';
const locale = 'en-US';
const timezone1 = '-4'; // this is the offset from GMT of date1 in US/Eastern time zone
const timezone2 = '-5'; // this is the offset from GMT of date2 in US/Eastern time zone

formatDate(date1, format, locale, timezone1);
formatDate(date2, format, locale, timezone2);

after:

const date1 = new Date('2022-08-28T15:00:00');
const date2 = new Date('2022-12-28T15:00:00');
const format = 'short';
const locale = 'en-US';
const timezone = 'US/Eastern';

formatDate(date1, format, locale, timezone);
formatDate(date2, format, locale, timezone);



### Proposed solution

Leverage the platform's Intl.DateTimeFormat, with option for a polyfill (such as this https://formatjs.io/docs/polyfills/intl-datetimeformat/) for platforms that don't have that


### Alternatives considered

none

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

core

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

Currently, the `RootViewRef` class is used to keep track of the underlying view for components created via `ComponentRef`, [see here](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/9a623c03b27e35f23d4834188880a9d669020e30/packages/core/src/render3/component_ref.ts#L279). When the view is change-detected, the following function is used:
https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/9a623c03b27e35f23d4834188880a9d669020e30/packages/core/src/render3/instructions/shared.ts#L483-L505
which is similar to the `detectChangesInternal` used elsewhere (for non-root views):
https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/9a623c03b27e35f23d4834188880a9d669020e30/packages/core/src/render3/instructions/shared.ts#L1806-L1817
The mentioned functions are very similar, but they have one big difference: the function for non-root views reports errors to the ErrorHandler, when a root view one does not.

This is not an issue in most cases, since there are other points at which the error is intercepted and reports. For example, this function is used during the bootstrap: https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/9a623c03b27e35f23d4834188880a9d669020e30/packages/core/src/application_ref.ts#L594.
and also when an error happens in a listener:
https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/9a623c03b27e35f23d4834188880a9d669020e30/packages/core/src/render3/instructions/listener.ts#L220

However when an APIs like `createComponent` (and I suspect `ViewContainerRef.createComponent`) are used after the bootstrap and outside of listeners, errors would not be reported to the `ErrorHandler`. Here is a TestBed test to illustrate this:
```
   fit('should report errors to the ErrorHandler', () => {
      @Component({
        standalone: true,
        template: '...',
      })
      class StandaloneComponent {
        ngOnInit() {
          throw new Error('!');
        }
      }

      let errorHandlerInvoked = false;
      const hostElement = document.createElement('div');
      const parentInjector = TestBed.inject(EnvironmentInjector);
      const errorHandler = {
        handleError: () => {
          errorHandlerInvoked = true;
        }
      };
      const providers = [
        {provide: ErrorHandler, useValue: errorHandler},
      ];
      const environmentInjector = createEnvironmentInjector(providers, parentInjector);
      const componentRef = createComponent(StandaloneComponent, {hostElement, environmentInjector});
      expect(() => {
        componentRef.changeDetectorRef.detectChanges();
      }).toThrow();

      // This assert fails (ErrorHandler is never invoked):
      expect(errorHandlerInvoked).toBe(true);
    });
```
It's easy to add a logic to report errors:
```
--- a/packages/core/src/render3/instructions/shared.ts
+++ b/packages/core/src/render3/instructions/shared.ts
@@ -497,6 +497,9 @@ export function renderComponentOrTemplate<T>(
       renderView(tView, lView, context);
     }
     refreshView(tView, lView, templateFn, context);
+  } catch (error) {
+    handleError(lView, error);
+    throw error;
   } finally {
     if (!checkNoChangesMode && !creationModeIsActive && rendererFactory.end) {
       rendererFactory.end();
```
However this would have consequences for the mentioned cases (bootstrapping, event listeners invocation) and would result in reporting an error to the ErrorHandler twice. As a possible solution, we can probably mark (via monkey-patching) errors that we've reported and skip reporting it the second time.

Another API that would likely be affected: `TestBed.createComponent`.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

forms

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

I have a form service with 3 fields dependent on each other: when one of them is used, the others become required.

```ts
class FormService {
  controlA: FormControl = new FormControl('', [
    requiredIfOtherIsUsedValidator(() => this.controlB),
    requiredIfOtherIsUsedValidator(() => this.controlC),
  ]);

  controlB: FormControl = new FormControl('', [
    requiredIfOtherIsUsedValidator(() => this.controlA),
    requiredIfOtherIsUsedValidator(() => this.controlC),
  ]);

  controlC: FormControl = new FormControl('', [
    requiredIfOtherIsUsedValidator(() => this.controlA),
    requiredIfOtherIsUsedValidator(() => this.controlB),
  ]);

  form = new FormGroup({
    controlA: this.controlA,
    controlB: this.controlB,
    controlC: this.controlC,
  });
}
```

I wrote a custom form validator to make it work:

```ts
/** Marks control as required if other control is not empty */
export function requiredIfOtherIsUsedValidator(
  otherControlGetter: () => AbstractControl | undefined
): ValidatorFn {
  return (control: AbstractControl): ValidationErrors | null => {
    const otherControl = otherControlGetter();
    if (otherControl) {
      const otherIsUsed = !!otherControl.value;
      if (otherIsUsed && !control.value) {
        return { required: true };
      }
    }
    return null;
  };
}
```

When I reset the form (i.e.: when all the form fields are cleared), I expect all the fields to become not required and to be valid.
This is not the case (please check the stackblitz):

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43757707/187181562-aead33ee-09f4-469d-9e78-ae56e15d5b2d.png)


### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-o4y1km?file=src%2Fapp%2Futils%2Frequired-if-other-is-used-validator.spec.ts

### Please provide the exception or error you saw

_No response_

### Please provide the environment you discovered this bug in (run `ng version`)

Stackblitz environment with latest version of Angular 14

### Anything else?

I *think* that this is a bug, but maybe it is as expected (?). If so, please explain me why 🙏
In my case, I'll go with the `setValidators` approach as a workaround.
Thank you very much for your help 🙏

